1
00:02:27,387 --> 00:02:29,188
Can't believe it.
They're right on time.

2
00:02:29,255 --> 00:02:31,756
Let's get these boys
to their party.

3
00:02:51,378 --> 00:02:53,963
Mama!

4
00:03:24,147 --> 00:03:26,881
<i>It's 10:48
on Fat Tuesday, Mardi Gras.</i>

5
00:03:26,949 --> 00:03:29,768
<i>Now let's go back
in time to 1964.</i>

6
00:03:29,835 --> 00:03:33,222
<i>The Beach Boys on 105.3 FM,</i>

7
00:03:33,289 --> 00:03:35,475
<i>the heart of New Orleans.</i>

8
00:03:44,935 --> 00:03:47,654
<i>♪ Well it's been</i>
<i>building up inside of me</i>

9
00:03:47,721 --> 00:03:51,575
<i>♪ For oh I don't know</i>
<i>how long ♪</i>

10
00:04:00,251 --> 00:04:03,287
Okay. Take it out wide.
Give the pig some room.

11
00:04:08,175 --> 00:04:11,162
<i>♪ When she says</i>
<i>don't worry baby</i>

12
00:04:11,230 --> 00:04:14,265
<i>♪ Don't worry baby,</i>
<i>don't worry ♪</i>

13
00:04:26,912 --> 00:04:29,965
<i>♪ Don't worry baby</i>

14
00:04:33,069 --> 00:04:35,871
<i>♪ I guess I should have kept</i>
<i>my mouth shut</i>

15
00:04:35,938 --> 00:04:39,875
<i>♪ When I started to brag</i>
<i>about my car</i>

16
00:04:40,944 --> 00:04:43,545
<i>♪ But I can't back down now</i>

17
00:04:43,613 --> 00:04:48,851
<i>♪ Because I pushed</i>
<i>the other guys too far</i>

18
00:04:48,919 --> 00:04:52,772
<i>♪ She makes me come alive</i>

19
00:04:52,839 --> 00:04:56,994
<i>♪ And makes me wanna drive</i>
<i>when she says</i>

20
00:04:57,061 --> 00:05:00,864
<i>♪ Don't worry baby,</i>
<i>don't worry baby</i>

21
00:05:00,931 --> 00:05:02,415
<i>♪ Don't worry baby</i>

22
00:05:02,483 --> 00:05:04,735
<i>♪ Everything will turn out</i>
<i>all right ♪</i>

23
00:05:06,405 --> 00:05:08,205
<i>♪ Don't worry baby,</i>
<i>don't worry ♪</i>

24
00:06:52,883 --> 00:06:56,987
My daughter's on that ferry.
Please. Please.

25
00:06:57,054 --> 00:06:59,256
Oh, God, my daughter!

26
00:08:04,291 --> 00:08:05,941
Do the other side?

27
00:09:02,786 --> 00:09:04,788
ATF New Orleans,
Agent Donnelly.

28
00:09:04,856 --> 00:09:06,673
Listen,
call New Orleans PD.

29
00:09:06,741 --> 00:09:09,376
I want all surveillance
from the Algiers dock.

30
00:09:09,443 --> 00:09:10,661
Then call City Transit.

31
00:09:10,729 --> 00:09:13,079
I want the Crescent City
Bridge surveillance,

32
00:09:13,147 --> 00:09:14,548
<i>westbound between</i>
<i>10:00 and 11:00.</i>

33
00:09:14,933 --> 00:09:15,698
All right, got it.

34
00:09:56,192 --> 00:09:58,961
Hey. Seen an ATF
agent around here?

35
00:09:59,029 --> 00:10:00,663
Yeah,
he went down below.

36
00:10:01,549 --> 00:10:02,682
How do I get there?

37
00:10:02,850 --> 00:10:04,601
The south side
of the bridge.

38
00:10:12,527 --> 00:10:14,461
You Agent Minuti?

39
00:10:14,528 --> 00:10:16,596
Larry Minuti, ATF?

40
00:10:16,664 --> 00:10:19,133
No, Larry's my partner.
I'm Doug Carlin.

41
00:10:19,201 --> 00:10:21,252
Paul Pryzwarra, FBI.

42
00:10:21,319 --> 00:10:23,371
How you doing?
Where's Minuti?

43
00:10:23,439 --> 00:10:24,956
On vacation.

44
00:10:25,023 --> 00:10:28,609
Not anymore. We're calling in
half the region on this one.

45
00:10:28,677 --> 00:10:30,461
You can, uh, reach him?

46
00:10:30,529 --> 00:10:33,181
I tried. He's not
picking up his phone.

47
00:10:33,248 --> 00:10:36,468
Well, try harder.
It's important.

48
00:10:36,536 --> 00:10:37,869
Obviously.

49
00:10:39,038 --> 00:10:40,872
What are you
looking for?

50
00:10:41,024 --> 00:10:42,858
Anything that
doesn't belong.

51
00:10:46,446 --> 00:10:48,480
You want to give me a spot?

52
00:10:49,749 --> 00:10:50,949
Uh, yeah.

53
00:11:04,131 --> 00:11:05,665
ANFO.

54
00:11:05,733 --> 00:11:07,584
Ammonium nitrate,
water-soluble.

55
00:11:07,651 --> 00:11:10,520
Fuel oil would have burned
off during the blast.

56
00:11:10,721 --> 00:11:12,605
Between the river and the
rain, if ANFO was used,

57
00:11:12,673 --> 00:11:14,174
the only place you'd
find it would be...

58
00:11:14,241 --> 00:11:16,093
Underneath this bridge.

59
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:18,279
That's right.

60
00:11:18,430 --> 00:11:20,464
We can't rule out an accident
at this point.

61
00:11:20,532 --> 00:11:21,748
It's not officially
a crime scene yet.

62
00:11:21,816 --> 00:11:22,883
Here's a thought.

63
00:11:22,951 --> 00:11:24,317
Why don't we
double the perimeter

64
00:11:24,385 --> 00:11:25,986
so we don't have wall-to-wall
trailers down there?

65
00:11:26,053 --> 00:11:27,588
No, we're gonna need
all our manpower

66
00:11:27,655 --> 00:11:29,490
for evidence control
and witness processing.

67
00:11:29,557 --> 00:11:30,991
Now, we need to keep it tight

68
00:11:31,058 --> 00:11:33,227
until we can determine that
it is a crime investigation.

69
00:11:33,295 --> 00:11:35,513
It is a crime investigation.

70
00:11:35,581 --> 00:11:38,483
Got a piece of electric blasting
cap and a strand of leg wire.

71
00:11:41,337 --> 00:11:42,987
About a million of
those blue particles

72
00:11:43,055 --> 00:11:44,823
washed up on
the Algiers side.

73
00:11:44,890 --> 00:11:47,609
It's probably from a plastic
container or a barrel.

74
00:11:47,677 --> 00:11:48,977
ANFO?

75
00:11:49,045 --> 00:11:50,612
Most likely.
There was post-blast residue

76
00:11:50,681 --> 00:11:52,614
under the Crescent
City Bridge.

77
00:11:52,683 --> 00:11:55,417
The insulation on the
leg wire will inform us

78
00:11:55,485 --> 00:11:57,653
of who the manufacturer
of the blasting cap is.

79
00:11:57,721 --> 00:11:59,355
Then we go after
the switching mechanism

80
00:11:59,423 --> 00:12:00,956
and the bomb's
power source.

81
00:12:01,024 --> 00:12:02,675
We probably don't need
to wait for the lab

82
00:12:02,693 --> 00:12:04,176
to tell us what
we already know,

83
00:12:04,244 --> 00:12:06,428
that this is an explosive
and a trigger.

84
00:12:06,496 --> 00:12:07,897
And you are?

85
00:12:07,965 --> 00:12:10,266
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm Doug Carlin, ATF.

86
00:12:10,334 --> 00:12:12,052
Who's in charge?
We're working on that now.

87
00:12:12,120 --> 00:12:13,270
Gentlemen, please.

88
00:12:13,337 --> 00:12:15,155
Ed Elkins. I'm in charge.

89
00:12:15,222 --> 00:12:16,323
Oh, good, good, good.
Yeah.

90
00:12:16,390 --> 00:12:18,158
You're in charge, then?
Okay.

91
00:12:18,226 --> 00:12:20,193
First things first.
Where's the coffeepot?

92
00:12:20,260 --> 00:12:21,811
Ed?

93
00:12:21,963 --> 00:12:24,465
Come on, this is a police
investigation, right? Operation.

94
00:12:24,532 --> 00:12:26,249
We gotta have a coffeepot.

95
00:12:26,317 --> 00:12:28,136
Yeah, uh, uh,
you'll find it in the back.

96
00:12:28,138 --> 00:12:29,403
Back there?
Yeah.

97
00:12:29,471 --> 00:12:31,372
He is in charge.
Thank you, gentlemen.

98
00:12:54,814 --> 00:12:56,198
See anything?

99
00:12:56,265 --> 00:12:57,516
Uh, traffic.

100
00:12:57,584 --> 00:12:59,001
Hit rewind for me.

101
00:13:00,369 --> 00:13:02,137
Hey, did Larry call?

102
00:13:02,139 --> 00:13:03,689
Still not answering his cell.
We left another message.

103
00:13:03,757 --> 00:13:05,024
All right.

104
00:13:05,092 --> 00:13:06,960
Say, that girl ever get ahold of you?
What girl?

105
00:13:07,027 --> 00:13:09,595
You know, sexy voice, asked if you
were tall, dark and handsome.

106
00:13:09,663 --> 00:13:11,097
I gave her two out of three.

107
00:13:11,165 --> 00:13:12,382
Two out of three. That's very good.
Hit play.

108
00:13:12,449 --> 00:13:14,383
Thank you.

109
00:13:19,122 --> 00:13:20,657
Hey, Larry, this is Doug.
How you doing?

110
00:13:20,724 --> 00:13:22,626
Listen, I know you're maybe
still pissed off at me,

111
00:13:22,694 --> 00:13:24,595
but you need to get your
behind down here, all right?

112
00:13:24,663 --> 00:13:25,946
Doug.
Yeah?

113
00:13:26,014 --> 00:13:27,882
Doug, Orleans Parish on line one.
It's Sheriff Reed.

114
00:13:27,949 --> 00:13:30,184
They pulled a body out of the
water, and they want a profile.

115
00:13:30,252 --> 00:13:31,919
All right, tell him
they don't need a profile.

116
00:13:31,987 --> 00:13:33,587
Just tell him to bag it.
I'll call him back.

117
00:13:33,789 --> 00:13:35,239
Okay, got it.

118
00:13:36,891 --> 00:13:38,325
Put this on
a candy wrapper?

119
00:13:38,393 --> 00:13:39,610
It's all I had.

120
00:13:39,678 --> 00:13:41,696
Cutting back, huh?

121
00:13:43,482 --> 00:13:45,250
Hold it right there.

122
00:13:47,136 --> 00:13:50,472
Yeah, this is ATF Agent Doug
Carlin returning your call.

123
00:13:50,540 --> 00:13:53,808
My cell number
is 504-555-0130.

124
00:13:54,377 --> 00:13:55,660
What's that?

125
00:13:55,728 --> 00:13:57,412
Looks like
a dude on a bike.

126
00:13:57,414 --> 00:13:59,382
Run it forward
a little bit.

127
00:14:01,401 --> 00:14:02,635
Stop right there.

128
00:14:05,439 --> 00:14:07,339
What is he doing?

129
00:14:08,525 --> 00:14:09,826
Going to the bathroom?

130
00:14:14,764 --> 00:14:16,982
Run it forward,
run it forward.

131
00:14:21,373 --> 00:14:22,622
What time does it say?

132
00:14:22,690 --> 00:14:23,841
10:47.

133
00:14:23,908 --> 00:14:25,525
That's before the explosion,
isn't it?

134
00:14:25,827 --> 00:14:27,277
Right before.

135
00:14:29,964 --> 00:14:31,231
<i>McCREADY: Can I have</i>
<i>your attention, please?</i>

136
00:14:31,299 --> 00:14:32,983
<i>Thanks very much for coming.</i>

137
00:14:32,985 --> 00:14:34,952
<i>I'm Jack McCready,</i>
<i>special agent</i>

138
00:14:35,019 --> 00:14:37,521
<i>in charge of</i>
<i>this investigation.</i>

139
00:14:37,589 --> 00:14:39,707
<i>First, let me say</i>
<i>our hearts go out</i>

140
00:14:39,775 --> 00:14:42,210
<i>to all of those</i>
<i>affected by this tragedy.</i>

141
00:14:44,280 --> 00:14:46,815
<i>Early estimates place</i>
<i>the number of casualties</i>

142
00:14:46,882 --> 00:14:51,736
<i>at 543 men,</i>
<i>women and children.</i>

143
00:14:51,803 --> 00:14:54,523
<i>Now, Lord knows this city</i>
<i>has seen its share of pain,</i>

144
00:14:54,590 --> 00:14:56,943
<i>but unlike Katrina,</i>

145
00:14:57,010 --> 00:15:00,545
<i>this disaster was</i>
<i>not an act of nature.</i>

146
00:15:00,613 --> 00:15:03,248
<i>After careful review of evidence
retrieved at the scene,</i>

147
00:15:03,316 --> 00:15:07,519
<i>we have concluded this was</i>
<i>a deliberate act of terrorism,</i>

148
00:15:07,587 --> 00:15:10,222
<i>and the President concurs</i>
<i>with our assessment.</i>

149
00:15:10,290 --> 00:15:12,926
<i>On our end, we have to
ask for your patience,</i>

150
00:15:12,994 --> 00:15:14,711
<i>as the investigation</i>
<i>will take time.</i>

151
00:15:14,778 --> 00:15:18,665
<i>It's a unique and complicated</i>
<i>crime scene.</i>

152
00:15:18,733 --> 00:15:22,636
<i>There's no baggage checks.
There's no flight data recorder.</i>

153
00:15:22,703 --> 00:15:24,320
<i>There are maximum casualties,</i>

154
00:15:24,388 --> 00:15:28,108
<i>and most of the evidence is
under 100 feet of muddy water.</i>

155
00:15:29,577 --> 00:15:31,462
<i>There are no shortcuts.</i>

156
00:15:33,899 --> 00:15:34,966
Kevin, where's Doug?

157
00:15:35,033 --> 00:15:36,284
You just missed him.

158
00:15:36,351 --> 00:15:37,201
Well, his car's still here.

159
00:15:37,269 --> 00:15:38,302
Took the streetcar.

160
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:39,503
What? Streetcar?

161
00:15:39,571 --> 00:15:40,938
Hey, don't look at me.

162
00:15:41,006 --> 00:15:43,741
It's part of his process.
He says it helps him think.

163
00:15:49,348 --> 00:15:50,349
Sheriff Reed.

164
00:15:51,984 --> 00:15:54,018
How you doing?
It's Doug Carlin returning your call.

165
00:15:54,086 --> 00:15:56,605
Hey, Doug. I know you got
your hands full right now.

166
00:15:56,723 --> 00:15:58,824
Yeah, that's okay.
What do you got for me, Bob?

167
00:15:58,892 --> 00:16:00,926
Well, a couple of kids
found a woman

168
00:16:00,994 --> 00:16:02,928
face down in the waters
off Algiers Point.

169
00:16:02,995 --> 00:16:05,497
She was burned
over 30% of her body.

170
00:16:05,565 --> 00:16:08,234
Right, well, you're gonna see a lot
of that over the next few weeks.

171
00:16:08,302 --> 00:16:09,953
We've just set up ECC.

172
00:16:10,021 --> 00:16:11,888
Just have Crime Scene
bag it for us.

173
00:16:11,956 --> 00:16:14,523
<i>Well, we already done that.
The body's at the ME's right now.</i>

174
00:16:14,591 --> 00:16:16,409
Crime Scene's
already been there?

175
00:16:16,477 --> 00:16:17,977
<i>Yeah, they've been and gone.</i>

176
00:16:18,045 --> 00:16:21,130
Well, exactly what time did
this woman wash up on shore?

177
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:26,135
Kid called it in
at 10:42 a.m.

178
00:16:27,055 --> 00:16:28,689
You mean 11:42, don't you?

179
00:16:28,757 --> 00:16:32,059
No, I mean 10:42.
I got the sheet right in front of me,

180
00:16:32,127 --> 00:16:34,378
and I got my
reading glasses on.

181
00:16:38,934 --> 00:16:42,836
Immediately evident is the focal
charring of the limbs and torso.

182
00:16:44,322 --> 00:16:48,393
Anterior face, neck and chest
are intact,

183
00:16:48,461 --> 00:16:51,329
though swollen from apparent
immersion in water.

184
00:17:00,823 --> 00:17:02,106
Hold her hand
for me, will you?

185
00:17:02,108 --> 00:17:03,358
Right here.

186
00:17:04,695 --> 00:17:06,278
There we go.

187
00:17:06,280 --> 00:17:09,165
Each digit of the right hand
has been severed

188
00:17:09,232 --> 00:17:12,985
between the middle and
distal phalanges. Thanks.

189
00:17:13,053 --> 00:17:16,889
Angle of shearing indicates
a single sharp-force trauma,

190
00:17:16,956 --> 00:17:18,757
possibly caused
by shrapnel.

191
00:17:18,825 --> 00:17:22,462
No. No, it's too even
to be shrapnel trauma.

192
00:17:23,681 --> 00:17:26,700
Posterior charring
gives off a strong odor,

193
00:17:26,767 --> 00:17:29,702
suggesting perimortem
immersion in burning fuel.

194
00:17:30,604 --> 00:17:31,838
Diesel.

195
00:17:31,906 --> 00:17:33,907
Accelerant, maybe?
I don't know.

196
00:17:33,974 --> 00:17:35,375
If she was that close
to the bomb,

197
00:17:35,443 --> 00:17:37,578
she probably wouldn't
be laying here now.

198
00:17:38,713 --> 00:17:40,181
What are you doing?

199
00:17:41,082 --> 00:17:43,233
What are you doing?

200
00:17:43,301 --> 00:17:44,636
You got a UV gun?

201
00:17:44,638 --> 00:17:46,353
Yeah,
on the table behind you.

202
00:17:49,975 --> 00:17:51,108
You see that?

203
00:17:51,127 --> 00:17:53,010
Duct tape.
Mmm-hmm.

204
00:17:54,863 --> 00:17:56,797
What's that stippling?
You see that?

205
00:17:56,865 --> 00:17:59,634
Adhesive probably retained some
substance against the water.

206
00:17:59,702 --> 00:18:01,220
Yeah.

207
00:18:06,492 --> 00:18:07,525
Yeah, go ahead.

208
00:18:07,593 --> 00:18:09,528
I ran down
those MPRs for you.

209
00:18:09,596 --> 00:18:12,881
A Claire Kuchever was reported
missing this morning.

210
00:18:12,949 --> 00:18:14,583
<i>Supposed to pick up her
father from the airport,</i>

211
00:18:14,651 --> 00:18:15,884
<i>pulled a no-show.</i>

212
00:18:15,952 --> 00:18:17,086
Okay.

213
00:18:18,688 --> 00:18:21,841
All right, Phil, I want
you to do a full autopsy.

214
00:18:21,909 --> 00:18:24,144
Concentrate on
time and cause.

215
00:18:25,963 --> 00:18:27,830
Full spread of lab tests.
Everything.

216
00:18:27,898 --> 00:18:31,200
Just pretend like the ferry explosion
never happened today, okay?

217
00:18:31,269 --> 00:18:32,736
Absolutely.

218
00:18:36,257 --> 00:18:37,374
Claire?

219
00:18:41,647 --> 00:18:43,431
She's beautiful, huh?

220
00:18:43,498 --> 00:18:44,565
Yeah.

221
00:18:44,633 --> 00:18:45,816
Very.

222
00:19:17,500 --> 00:19:20,169
You'll need a photograph for
your investigation, right?

223
00:19:21,605 --> 00:19:24,506
There's plenty in the house.
Plenty to choose from.

224
00:19:27,528 --> 00:19:31,197
Mr. Kuchever,
I'm sorry about this,

225
00:19:34,402 --> 00:19:37,504
but I'm gonna need you to confirm
your daughter's identity.

226
00:19:43,377 --> 00:19:45,312
Okay.

227
00:19:45,379 --> 00:19:49,484
Uh, now, anything
that you can tell me

228
00:19:49,551 --> 00:19:52,587
about your daughter's
activities over the weekend,

229
00:19:52,654 --> 00:19:55,706
or any time, anything at
all, will be helpful.

230
00:19:55,774 --> 00:19:57,542
Well, I don't know.

231
00:19:57,577 --> 00:19:59,527
My flight got in
at 8:00 a.m. this morning,

232
00:19:59,595 --> 00:20:02,696
and she was supposed to pick
me up, but she wasn't there.

233
00:20:02,764 --> 00:20:04,632
I thought maybe
she just overslept,

234
00:20:04,700 --> 00:20:07,970
so I took a cab and I went
straight to her house.

235
00:20:08,038 --> 00:20:09,572
Her and Alan's car was gone,

236
00:20:09,623 --> 00:20:12,408
so I thought maybe she'd
just finally sold it.

237
00:20:12,476 --> 00:20:14,744
Who's Alan?
Her fiance.

238
00:20:14,811 --> 00:20:16,528
Or ex-fiance.

239
00:20:16,596 --> 00:20:19,165
They broke up
a few months ago.

240
00:20:19,232 --> 00:20:20,866
And where is he now, Alan?

241
00:20:20,933 --> 00:20:22,501
He moved to Montreal.

242
00:20:22,503 --> 00:20:24,203
Okay.

243
00:20:24,271 --> 00:20:26,923
She was too good
for him, anyway.

244
00:20:26,991 --> 00:20:29,592
I got a sweater that she left,
if you want to take it.

245
00:20:29,660 --> 00:20:31,611
No, that's okay.
But if you have keys

246
00:20:31,679 --> 00:20:33,697
to her house,
I would appreciate it.

247
00:20:35,616 --> 00:20:38,251
Oh, she--she had a date.

248
00:20:38,319 --> 00:20:40,053
Last night on the phone,
she told me that

249
00:20:40,121 --> 00:20:42,038
she was gonna
meet someone,

250
00:20:42,106 --> 00:20:43,439
but she didn't say who.

251
00:20:43,507 --> 00:20:45,126
Her friend Beth
set it up.

252
00:20:45,194 --> 00:20:46,977
Beth.

253
00:20:47,045 --> 00:20:50,331
Beth Walsh. Claire baby-sits her
daughter, Abbey, sometimes.

254
00:20:50,399 --> 00:20:51,465
Okay.

255
00:20:53,535 --> 00:20:55,453
Thank you.

256
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:57,421
That's good for now.

257
00:20:59,557 --> 00:21:01,342
Somebody'll be in touch.

258
00:21:04,380 --> 00:21:05,914
Agent Carlin?

259
00:21:07,016 --> 00:21:08,166
Doug.

260
00:21:08,234 --> 00:21:10,252
I want you
to take these.

261
00:21:11,403 --> 00:21:12,604
Well, that's...

262
00:21:12,606 --> 00:21:16,658
Just go through them
when you get a chance.

263
00:21:16,726 --> 00:21:17,977
Well, it's really
not necessary.

264
00:21:18,044 --> 00:21:19,928
Yes, it is.

265
00:21:19,996 --> 00:21:23,499
See, I know how these
things go, Agent Carlin,

266
00:21:23,701 --> 00:21:25,751
and I need her
to matter to you.

267
00:23:18,939 --> 00:23:21,106
Monday, 7:48 p.m.

268
00:23:21,173 --> 00:23:23,074
<i>Hi, Claire. It's Dad.</i>

269
00:23:23,142 --> 00:23:25,377
<i>My flight gets in</i>
<i>at 7:55 tomorrow morning,</i>

270
00:23:25,445 --> 00:23:28,880
<i>so don't stay up too late.</i>
<i>Love you. Bye-bye.</i>

271
00:23:28,948 --> 00:23:32,001
Tuesday, 9:44 a.m.

272
00:23:32,069 --> 00:23:34,220
<i>Claire? Hi, it's Beth.</i>
<i>Are you there?</i>

273
00:23:34,288 --> 00:23:35,688
<i>I'm sorry</i>
<i>to call you so early,</i>

274
00:23:35,756 --> 00:23:37,257
<i>but you said you were gonna
call me when you got home,</i>

275
00:23:37,458 --> 00:23:38,774
<i>and when you didn't,</i>
<i>I started to get worried.</i>

276
00:23:38,842 --> 00:23:41,194
<i>- Beth, is this a joke?</i>
<i>- Oh, hey, hey! No.</i>

277
00:23:41,261 --> 00:23:42,979
<i>Like--Like I said, I was just
worried about you, that's all.</i>

278
00:23:43,047 --> 00:23:45,298
<i>I can't talk right now. Someone's
here. I'll call you later.</i>

279
00:23:45,366 --> 00:23:46,633
<i>Claire...</i>

280
00:23:49,704 --> 00:23:52,156
Tuesday, 9:50 a.m.

281
00:23:57,195 --> 00:24:00,848
<i>Tuesday, 10:04 a.m.</i>

282
00:24:00,916 --> 00:24:04,952
<i>Claire, it's Dad.</i>
<i>I did say 7:55, didn't I?</i>

283
00:24:05,019 --> 00:24:07,121
<i>I'm here at the airport,</i>
<i>waiting for you.</i>

284
00:24:07,189 --> 00:24:10,442
<i>If you're not coming, I hope
you're sending Beth or someone.</i>

285
00:24:10,510 --> 00:24:12,310
<i>Call me.</i>

286
00:24:14,163 --> 00:24:17,182
Tuesday, 1:18 p.m.

287
00:24:17,250 --> 00:24:20,385
<i>Yeah, this is ATF Agent Doug
Carlin returning your call.</i>

288
00:24:20,453 --> 00:24:23,571
<i>My cell number</i>
<i>is 504-555-0130.</i>

289
00:24:34,268 --> 00:24:37,686
<i>WOMAN Tuesday, 1:18 p.m.</i>

290
00:24:37,754 --> 00:24:41,123
<i>Yeah, this is ATF Agent Doug
Carlin returning your call.</i>

291
00:24:41,191 --> 00:24:44,544
<i>My cell number</i>
<i>is 504-555-0130.</i>

292
00:24:59,477 --> 00:25:02,563
The blast wave initiated
here, hit the bulkhead

293
00:25:02,630 --> 00:25:05,299
and propagated fore and aft along
the path of least resistance

294
00:25:05,468 --> 00:25:07,952
until it hits
this access hatch.

295
00:25:08,020 --> 00:25:09,970
Uh, and that's where
it gets really bad.

296
00:25:10,038 --> 00:25:11,339
<i>The blast wave continues</i>

297
00:25:11,407 --> 00:25:13,741
<i>into the engine room,</i>
<i>bursting the fuel tanks.</i>

298
00:25:13,809 --> 00:25:16,193
<i>This utility shaft here</i>
<i>acts like a chimney,</i>

299
00:25:16,261 --> 00:25:18,796
<i>draws the thermal components</i>
<i>into the engine room,</i>

300
00:25:18,864 --> 00:25:21,984
which ignites the fuel vapor,
causing a secondary explosion

301
00:25:22,052 --> 00:25:24,420
of far greater magnitude.

302
00:25:24,422 --> 00:25:25,987
Essentially,
the initial device

303
00:25:26,055 --> 00:25:27,756
turns the whole ferry
into a bomb

304
00:25:27,824 --> 00:25:29,758
and detonates it.

305
00:25:29,826 --> 00:25:31,744
And so our early guess

306
00:25:31,812 --> 00:25:34,062
is that the bomb vehicle
was a minivan or SUV.

307
00:25:34,130 --> 00:25:35,730
Possibly red or tan.

308
00:25:35,798 --> 00:25:37,199
McCREADY: Make and model?

309
00:25:37,266 --> 00:25:39,035
Take weeks,
maybe months.

310
00:25:39,102 --> 00:25:41,271
I got a partial on
the license plate.

311
00:25:43,441 --> 00:25:44,958
Shit.

312
00:25:45,026 --> 00:25:47,427
Check all the SUVs and minivans
that are registered in the state.

313
00:25:47,494 --> 00:25:49,146
Anything recently
rented or purchased,

314
00:25:49,213 --> 00:25:51,748
anything tied to a theft
or a missing persons report.

315
00:25:51,815 --> 00:25:53,033
Agent McCready?
Yeah.

316
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:54,851
Doug Carlin, ATF.

317
00:25:55,820 --> 00:25:57,888
Oh, yeah. Oklahoma City.

318
00:25:57,955 --> 00:26:00,007
Right. That's right.

319
00:26:00,075 --> 00:26:01,842
This afternoon,
I witnessed an autopsy

320
00:26:01,910 --> 00:26:05,697
of a young woman who washed
up off the Poland Wharf.

321
00:26:05,764 --> 00:26:09,250
Heavy fuel burns,
traces of PETN on her face.

322
00:26:09,317 --> 00:26:13,121
PETN, that's the base explosive
used by domestic terrorists.

323
00:26:13,188 --> 00:26:17,609
She also lost several fingers in
what appeared to be blast damage.

324
00:26:17,677 --> 00:26:19,144
Appeared?

325
00:26:19,212 --> 00:26:21,696
That's right. I checked the tide tables
against the position of the blast.

326
00:26:21,764 --> 00:26:24,383
For her to have washed up that
early and that far upriver,

327
00:26:24,450 --> 00:26:25,584
she would've had
to have been killed

328
00:26:25,652 --> 00:26:27,435
two hours before
the ferry exploded.

329
00:26:28,054 --> 00:26:29,321
Before?

330
00:26:31,257 --> 00:26:33,041
She died before
the explosion?

331
00:26:33,193 --> 00:26:34,860
She died before
the explosion, yeah.

332
00:26:34,928 --> 00:26:36,962
Her name is
Claire Kuchever.

333
00:26:37,030 --> 00:26:40,683
She washed up before the
explosion and against the tide.

334
00:26:40,751 --> 00:26:42,285
Do you have a scenario?

335
00:26:42,353 --> 00:26:43,986
Yes, I do.

336
00:26:44,054 --> 00:26:47,257
I believe that somebody abducted
her in her home, taped her mouth,

337
00:26:47,324 --> 00:26:50,160
bound her wrists, burned her
alive, dumped her in the river

338
00:26:50,227 --> 00:26:53,430
so she would appear to be
just another disaster victim.

339
00:26:54,165 --> 00:26:55,966
A disaster that
hadn't happened yet.

340
00:26:56,033 --> 00:26:58,686
But the PETN tells us

341
00:26:58,754 --> 00:27:01,305
that the bomber came in direct
contact with the victim.

342
00:27:01,373 --> 00:27:03,407
You solve her case,
you solve this case.

343
00:27:04,125 --> 00:27:05,742
Why this woman?

344
00:27:05,810 --> 00:27:08,528
Good question.
Her SUV is missing.

345
00:27:09,764 --> 00:27:12,400
It's a tan and red Bronco.

346
00:27:12,468 --> 00:27:16,387
It could have been stolen to
drive the bomb to the ferry.

347
00:27:16,455 --> 00:27:17,705
Oh, one more thing.

348
00:27:17,773 --> 00:27:20,708
The victim called
the local ATF office

349
00:27:20,776 --> 00:27:23,078
the morning
of the explosion.

350
00:27:23,979 --> 00:27:25,063
Yeah.

351
00:27:26,048 --> 00:27:27,114
We'll look into it.

352
00:27:27,182 --> 00:27:28,215
Okay.

353
00:27:29,318 --> 00:27:30,953
All right.

354
00:27:31,488 --> 00:27:32,822
Okay.

355
00:27:42,482 --> 00:27:44,166
Where's Larry?

356
00:27:44,233 --> 00:27:46,268
What?
Larry Minuti, my partner.

357
00:27:46,336 --> 00:27:49,690
That's his car right there.
Is he here?

358
00:27:49,757 --> 00:27:52,259
I thought you said
he was on vacation.

359
00:27:52,327 --> 00:27:54,228
Yeah, that's right.

360
00:27:56,881 --> 00:27:58,247
What?

361
00:28:01,452 --> 00:28:05,522
Those cars were brought here from
the Algiers ferry parking lot.

362
00:28:05,589 --> 00:28:08,859
They're the vehicles
that belonged to the victims.

363
00:28:23,325 --> 00:28:25,159
Sorry.

364
00:28:39,993 --> 00:28:41,443
So he's a former Marine?

365
00:28:41,511 --> 00:28:43,528
Yes, sir. Yeah. Local, too.

366
00:28:43,596 --> 00:28:45,815
He's born and bred
in New Orleans.

367
00:28:45,882 --> 00:28:47,300
His family
still in the area?

368
00:28:47,367 --> 00:28:50,369
Nope. Nothing, really,
but his job.

369
00:28:50,437 --> 00:28:51,520
You like him?

370
00:28:51,589 --> 00:28:53,089
He's smart.

371
00:28:53,156 --> 00:28:54,991
Yeah, I like him, too.

372
00:28:55,059 --> 00:28:56,610
All right.
Let's go find him.

373
00:29:22,789 --> 00:29:24,289
Oklahoma City.

374
00:29:27,794 --> 00:29:28,893
Yeah.

375
00:29:32,932 --> 00:29:34,299
You and Larry were close?

376
00:29:34,367 --> 00:29:35,967
Yeah.

377
00:29:36,035 --> 00:29:40,707
Yeah, you know, close enough
to get on each other's nerves.

378
00:29:40,774 --> 00:29:45,077
Doug, I've been put in charge of a
newly-formed investigative unit.

379
00:29:45,145 --> 00:29:48,948
The ferry disaster is our first
case, and I want you on the team.

380
00:29:49,016 --> 00:29:50,616
Why me?

381
00:29:50,684 --> 00:29:53,485
We've got some unique
time constraints.

382
00:29:53,553 --> 00:29:57,958
I need someone who can look at a
crime scene exactly one time,

383
00:29:58,026 --> 00:30:01,228
tell us what's missing, tell
us what shouldn't be there,

384
00:30:01,296 --> 00:30:02,629
tell us what
we can ignore

385
00:30:02,697 --> 00:30:05,132
and, especially,
what we need to pursue.

386
00:30:05,200 --> 00:30:08,635
Also, you're local. You know the
people and you know the area.

387
00:30:08,703 --> 00:30:10,603
But why an ATF guy?

388
00:30:10,671 --> 00:30:13,273
Why not?
It's your shot.

389
00:30:13,275 --> 00:30:15,992
You want to find the guy
who killed Minuti, don't you?

390
00:30:18,797 --> 00:30:20,030
Yes, I do.

391
00:30:43,340 --> 00:30:45,408
I guess you've
got some questions.

392
00:30:45,475 --> 00:30:49,245
For me to have questions, first
I'd need to know something.

393
00:31:17,559 --> 00:31:19,260
Now I do have
some questions.

394
00:31:19,327 --> 00:31:21,912
Don't touch anything.
We don't need you yet.

395
00:31:21,980 --> 00:31:24,765
Doug, you remember
Dr. Alexander Denny.

396
00:31:25,801 --> 00:31:27,368
Where's my audio?

397
00:31:27,436 --> 00:31:29,922
Compensating for audio delay.
Just a second.

398
00:31:31,607 --> 00:31:33,809
Oh, compensating for a technical
blunder by a tech guy...

399
00:31:33,876 --> 00:31:35,376
Solid stream.
Minus four days,

400
00:31:35,444 --> 00:31:37,946
six hours, three
minutes, 45 seconds.

401
00:31:38,014 --> 00:31:40,249
And 14 and
a half nanoseconds.

402
00:31:40,800 --> 00:31:42,751
Okay.

403
00:31:42,819 --> 00:31:46,154
Anytime you want to jump
in here, be my guest.

404
00:31:46,222 --> 00:31:47,455
Me?
Yeah.

405
00:31:57,101 --> 00:31:58,551
What are we looking for?

406
00:31:58,619 --> 00:32:01,821
You know, clues, suspects,
anything out of the norm.

407
00:32:02,573 --> 00:32:03,790
When was this taken?

408
00:32:03,858 --> 00:32:04,724
Four and a half
days ago.

409
00:32:04,792 --> 00:32:07,094
Gunnars, try the guy
with the backpack.

410
00:32:14,402 --> 00:32:16,136
Oh, that's tender.

411
00:32:16,204 --> 00:32:18,506
I wish I had someone.
Okay, widen out.

412
00:32:18,573 --> 00:32:22,042
Let's cruise the car deck for
a while, see what we got.

413
00:32:26,699 --> 00:32:27,982
How can you
change the angle

414
00:32:28,050 --> 00:32:30,218
on footage taken
four and a half days ago?

415
00:32:30,286 --> 00:32:31,870
This is a digital recreation.

416
00:32:32,071 --> 00:32:34,906
We're combining all the data
we've got into one fluid shot.

417
00:32:34,974 --> 00:32:37,642
Any angle, any view
within the target area.

418
00:32:39,445 --> 00:32:41,713
Okay, um,
let's cruise the breezeway,

419
00:32:41,781 --> 00:32:44,283
see what we get there.

420
00:32:44,351 --> 00:32:46,435
It's a brand-new program.
It's called Snow White.

421
00:32:46,503 --> 00:32:48,788
Our primary data comes from
seven orbiting satellites,

422
00:32:48,855 --> 00:32:52,525
but at any given time, as many as
four are surveilling one area.

423
00:32:52,592 --> 00:32:54,427
It's like having
multiple eyewitnesses,

424
00:32:54,494 --> 00:32:57,296
each with their
own vantage point.

425
00:32:57,364 --> 00:32:58,831
Snow White?

426
00:33:03,505 --> 00:33:05,205
Well, which one
of the seven dwarfs

427
00:33:05,272 --> 00:33:08,041
can explain to me
how you get the audio?

428
00:33:13,097 --> 00:33:14,865
I don't understand.

429
00:33:16,234 --> 00:33:17,818
Why do you gotta
look at four days ago?

430
00:33:17,886 --> 00:33:20,638
Why don't you just fast-forward
it to the day of the explosion?

431
00:33:20,705 --> 00:33:22,590
We have to wait.
It takes four and a half days

432
00:33:22,658 --> 00:33:25,009
to render this
single fluid shot.

433
00:33:25,076 --> 00:33:26,444
The only thing
that matters

434
00:33:26,512 --> 00:33:30,714
is that we have exactly
one look at any one time.

435
00:33:30,782 --> 00:33:33,551
Yeah. We can't go back
10 minutes, you know?

436
00:33:33,619 --> 00:33:36,654
Can't look back and see
if there was a second gunman.

437
00:33:36,722 --> 00:33:41,126
We can't watch the agent buying
10 pairs of cargo pants in 1983.

438
00:33:42,512 --> 00:33:44,096
All right?
But given enough lead time,

439
00:33:44,163 --> 00:33:46,531
we can look anywhere within
the target area, all right?

440
00:33:46,600 --> 00:33:48,100
It's the when
that's always constant.

441
00:33:48,167 --> 00:33:50,502
It's always four days
and six hours ago.

442
00:33:50,570 --> 00:33:52,187
Always. You understand?

443
00:33:52,254 --> 00:33:57,693
It's like a single trailing
moment of now, in the past.

444
00:33:57,761 --> 00:34:02,798
Okay. So if--if--if--if you can't
move forward or backward in time,

445
00:34:02,834 --> 00:34:04,817
how is it the image keeps
speeding up like that?

446
00:34:04,885 --> 00:34:06,435
It's not the image
that's moving faster,

447
00:34:06,503 --> 00:34:08,171
it's just our
shifting point of view.

448
00:34:08,239 --> 00:34:09,672
The passage of time
remains constant,

449
00:34:09,740 --> 00:34:11,057
but we can shift
our point of view

450
00:34:11,125 --> 00:34:13,626
within the data stream
as fast as we want.

451
00:34:13,694 --> 00:34:15,462
You understand?

452
00:34:15,529 --> 00:34:17,598
Yeah. Yeah. No.

453
00:34:17,666 --> 00:34:19,016
Yeah, I know.

454
00:34:19,084 --> 00:34:20,884
So four days from...
Well, actually, three days from now,

455
00:34:20,952 --> 00:34:24,288
since it's after midnight,
you'll be able to look back

456
00:34:24,355 --> 00:34:26,090
to the day of the explosion,
see who did it,

457
00:34:26,158 --> 00:34:28,325
how they did it
and what they did it with.

458
00:34:28,393 --> 00:34:29,660
Yeah, you got it.

459
00:34:29,727 --> 00:34:31,562
The only thing is, you need
to tell us where to look,

460
00:34:31,629 --> 00:34:35,601
'cause, you know,
we could miss it.

461
00:34:35,668 --> 00:34:38,620
Besides, three days could be
too late. He could leave the country,

462
00:34:38,687 --> 00:34:40,371
could strike again.

463
00:34:40,439 --> 00:34:42,890
We need to do
whatever we can now.

464
00:34:42,892 --> 00:34:45,176
We know he's out there
planning this.

465
00:34:45,245 --> 00:34:47,412
We just don't
know where to look.

466
00:34:48,897 --> 00:34:51,266
So, Agent Carlin,
where do we look?

467
00:34:55,789 --> 00:34:57,590
Claire Kuchever's house.

468
00:35:00,227 --> 00:35:02,095
Address is in range.

469
00:35:02,162 --> 00:35:04,563
All right, match the viewer
settings to the signal.

470
00:35:08,736 --> 00:35:09,902
Signal's solid.

471
00:35:09,970 --> 00:35:11,504
All right, dazzle me.

472
00:35:26,488 --> 00:35:28,021
What?

473
00:35:28,089 --> 00:35:30,925
You see, with Snow White
we can track through walls.

474
00:35:30,993 --> 00:35:33,077
It's part of the same infrared
thermal-imaging stuff

475
00:35:33,145 --> 00:35:34,312
they're using in Iraq.

476
00:35:34,380 --> 00:35:36,081
<i>Hello. This is 877-504-8423.</i>

477
00:35:36,148 --> 00:35:38,199
We triangulate
from four satellites,

478
00:35:38,266 --> 00:35:40,251
pick up the heat signal
and reconstruct.

479
00:35:40,319 --> 00:35:42,503
Basically,
we can walk through walls.

480
00:35:44,623 --> 00:35:46,307
Claire Kuchever.

481
00:35:46,375 --> 00:35:47,508
<i>Claire? Hello?</i>

482
00:35:47,576 --> 00:35:49,145
Did you know her?

483
00:35:49,212 --> 00:35:51,847
We held hands once,
but no, I didn't know her.

484
00:35:51,914 --> 00:35:54,833
<i>Just checking in,</i>
<i>wondering how you're doing.</i>

485
00:35:54,901 --> 00:35:58,120
